  "prompt": "Do airplanes float on water?",
  "response": "Airplanes are not designed to float on water like boats, but some aircraft, particularly seaplanes and amphibious planes, are equipped with features that allow them to land on and take off from water. These aircraft have floats or hulls that provide buoyancy, enabling them to stay afloat.\n\nFor conventional airplanes, landing on water, known as a \"water landing\" or \"ditching,\" is extremely hazardous and not part of their design. While some large commercial airliners have been known to stay afloat for a short period after a controlled water landing, this is due to the aircraft's structure and the air trapped inside, not because they are designed to float. Over time, water will seep in, and the plane will sink.\n\nIn summary, while some specialized aircraft can float on water, most airplanes are not designed to do so and will eventually sink if they land on water.",
